## Diagnosis

The color-channel / weight-channel two-axis grammar is architecturally correct, but both axes are miscalibrated: the weight channel is stuck at `2px` for the resting state, making every Input read as "engaged" by default. The border should be a hairline (`1px`) at rest and step up to `2px` only on focus/engaged. This is a pure token-value error — the structure is fine, the numbers are wrong.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-072 — Stateful weight tokens collapsed to a single value**, causing the weight channel to carry no information. The resting and engaged states share the same thickness, so weight can no longer signal interaction state.

The likely offending token declaration:

```css
/* ❌ Before — both states resolve to 2px */
--input-border-width:         2px;   /* resting — should be 1px */
--input-border-width-engaged: 2px;   /* engaged — correct        */
```

---

## Fix

### 1. Correct the weight-channel tokens

**`src/styles/tokens/components/input.css`** (or wherever component tokens live)

```css
/* ✅ After */

/* ── Weight channel ─────────────────────────────────────────── */
--input-border-width:          1px;   /* resting  — hairline      */
--input-border-width-engaged:  2px;   /* engaged  — steps up      */

/* ── Color channel (unchanged — kept for reference) ─────────── */
--input-border-color:          var(--color-border-subtle);
--input-border-color-engaged:  var(--color-border-accent);
```

### 2. Verify the component consumes both axes correctly

**`src/components/elan/Input/Input.tsx`** (or `.module.css`)

```css
/* ── Resting ring: hairline, subtle color ────────────────────── */
.input {
  border-width: var(--input-border-width);          /* 1px */
  border-color: var(--input-border-color);
  border-style: solid;

  /* No box-shadow ring at rest */
  box-shadow: none;
}

/* ── Engaged ring: paint-only — NO layout shift ─────────────── */
/*    Use box-shadow to add the extra pixel, not border-width,   */
/*    so the element's box model stays stable.                   */
.input:focus-visible {
  border-width: var(--input-border-width);          /* still 1px  */
  border-color: var(--input-border-color-engaged);

  /* Inset shadow paints an extra 1px visually → reads as 2px    */
  box-shadow: inset 0 0 0 var(--input-border-width-engaged)
              var(--input-border-color-engaged);
}
```

> **Why `box-shadow` instead of `border-width: 2px` on focus?**  
> Changing `border-width` shifts the layout box by 1px, causing a micro-jitter on every focus event (CAP-016 — *layout-affecting state transitions*). The inset shadow paints identically but touches zero layout properties.

### 3. Smoke-test the visual axes

| State | Border width (layout) | Visual weight | Color |
|---|---|---|---|
| Resting | `1px` | hairline | `--color-border-subtle` |
| Hover | `1px` | hairline | `--color-border-default` *(optional)* |
| Focused | `1px` | `2px` via inset shadow | `--color-border-accent` |
| Error | `1px` | `2px` via inset shadow | `--color-border-error` |
| Disabled | `1px` | hairline | `--color-border-subtle` @ 40% opacity |

---

## Principle

**Two-axis interaction grammar requires distinct values on every axis at every meaningful state.** Color and weight are independent channels — color signals *kind* (neutral → accent → error), weight signals *degree of engagement* (resting → active). When both channels share the same value at rest and engaged, the weight axis carries zero information and the grammar collapses to a single-axis system. Resting must always be the minimum credible weight (`1px` / hairline); the engaged step-up (`2px`) is what makes the transition legible.
